title: ICE in nightly with assertion failed: !value.has_escaping_bound_vars()

labels.name: I-ICE
labels.description: Issue: The compiler panicked, giving an Internal Compilation Error (ICE) ❄️

labels.name: regression-from-stable-to-nightly
labels.description: Performance or correctness regression from stable to nightly.

labels.name: T-compiler
labels.description: Relevant to the compiler team, which will review and decide on the PR/issue.

body:
### Code ```Rust fn main() { test(&|| 0); } fn test(arg: &impl Fn() -> T) where for<'a> &'a T: Default {} ``` When creating this I found that it did not error if the function was not called and it also seemed to require it to be a function not just an argument of type T or (from what I tested) a different impl Trait although it could be any Fn* trait [Playground Link](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=4368c7e22b1e6ca1d825f52b7977c5d9) ### Meta `rustc --version --verbose`: ``` rustc 1.57.0-nightly (5ecc8ad84 2021-09-19) binary: rustc commit-hash: 5ecc8ad8462574354a55162a0c16b10eb95e3e70 commit-date: 2021-09-19 host: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu release: 1.57.0-nightly LLVM version: 13.0.0 ``` This appears to only happen on nightly while stable and beta generate useful error reports ### Error output ``` thread 'rustc' panicked at 'assertion failed: !value.has_escaping_bound_vars()',
